\c 58
\d From the Choirmaster’s collection. To the tune of “Destroy it not.” A golden ode of David.
\q
\v 1 Is it indeed justice you decree?
\q2 Is it aright that you rule men?
\q
\v 2 No, in secret you devise injustice,
\q2 and on earth you deal out violence.
\q
\v 3 Evil men go astray from the start,
\q2 false and erring from their birth;
\q
\v 4 their venom is like a viper’s
\q2 they are deaf as any cobra,
\q
\v 5 that will not listen to the charmer’s voice,
\q2 to the most cunning spell.
\q
\v 6 Shatter their teeth, O God!
\q2 O thou Eternal, tear out the young lions’ fangs!
\q
\v 7 May they vanish like a freshet,
\q2 may they be trodden down like the green grass!
\q
\v 8 May they melt like a snail as it moves,
\q2 like an untimely birth, unseen by the sun!
\q
\v 9 Ere ever your pot feels the heat of the faggots,
\q2 may He sweep them away in his fury!
\q
\v 10 At the sight of such vengeance, the good shall exult,
\q2 and bathe their feet in bad men’s blood;
\q
\v 11 “Yes,” men shall say, “the good do get their due;
\q2 yes, a God rules on earth indeed!”

\c 59
\d From the Choirmaster’s collection. To the tune of “Destroy it not.” A golden ode sung by David when Saul had the house watched, in order to murder him.
\q
\v 1 O my God, rescue me from my foes,
\q2 protect me from those who assail me;
\q
\v 2 rescue me from evildoers,
\q2 save me from bloodthirsty men.
\q
\v 3 Here they are, lurking to take my life,
\q2 a fierce gang to attack me!
\q And for no sin or crime of mine,
\q2 O thou Eternal, for no fault of mine.
\q
\v 4 They run to their posts; oh rouse thyself,
\q2 rescue me, look to me!
\q
\v 5 O Lord of hosts,
\q2 O God of Israel, rouse thee,
\q punish the insolent, every one of them,
\q2 spare not one vile traitor.
\q
\v 6 They snarl and snarl like dogs,
\q2 they prowl round the town in the evening;
\q
\v 7 there they are, blustering, arrogant,
\q2 insults on their lips! —
\q2 for “Who,” they think, “will hear us?”
\q
\v 8 Thou, O Eternal, thou wilt laugh at them,
\q2 wilt mock at all the insolent.
\q
\v 9 O thou my Strength, to thee I sing,
\q2 for thou, Eternal, art my fortress.
\q
\v 10 God in his goodness come to my rescue!
\q2 May the Eternal let me gloat over my foes!
\q
\v 11 Pity them not, lest my people forget;
\q2 rout them, ruin them, by thy might,
\q2 O Lord who art shielding me.
\b
\q
\v 12 Each word they utter is a sin;
\q2 so let their own pride trap them,
\q2 for all their perjury and false talk.
\q
\v 13 Destroy them in thy wrath, destroy them
\q2 till they cease to be;
\q let the world know from end to end
\q2 that God does rule in Jacob.
\b
\q
\v 14 They snarl and snarl like dogs,
\q2 and prowl at even round the town,
\q
\v 15 roaming in search of prey,
\q2 and growling if they miss it.
\q
\v 16 But I sing of thy strength,
\q2 a morning song to thy love;
\q for thou art a fortress to me,
\q2 a refuge in my day of danger.
\q
\v 17 O thou my Strength, to thee I sing,
\q2 for thou, Eternal, art my fortress.

\c 60
\d From the Choirmaster’s collection. To the tune of “Lily of the Law.” A golden ode for recitation, sung by David during the campaign against Aram-naharaim and Aram-zobah, when Joab wheeled round and defeated twelve thousand Edomites in the wady of Salt.
\q
\v 1 Thou hast discarded us, crushed us in anger, O God;
\q2 restore us to power:
\q
\v 2 thou hast shaken and shattered the land;
\q2 repair its tottering breaches.
\q
\v 3 Hard times thou hast given to thy people
\q2 and a cup to drink that has dazed them.
\q
\v 4 Hast thou given thy worshippers a flag,
\q2 only that they might fly from the archers?
\b
\q
\v 5 To the rescue of thy dear folk!
\q2 Save by thy right hand, answer our entreaty,
\q
\v 10b O thou Eternal who hast discarded us, shamed us,
\q2 who would’st not march out with our army.
\q
\v 11 Help us against the foe,
\q2 for man’s help is in vain.
\q
\v 12 With God we shall do bravely;
\q2 he will trample down our foes.
\b
\q
\v 6 God gave his sacred promise:
\q2 “I will divide up Shechem in triumph,
\q2 and parcel out the vale of Sukkoth;
\q
\v 7 Gilead is mine, Manasseh mine,
\q2 Ephraim I take for helmet,
\q2 Judah for my baton,
\q
\v 8 Moab I make a wash-basin,
\q2 Edom I claim as subject,
\q2 and over Philistia I will triumph.”
\q
\v 9 Ah, who will lead us inside the hill-fort?
\q2 Who will take us conquering into Edom?
\q2
\v 10a Wilt not thou, O God?

\c 61
\d From the Choirmaster’s collection. For strings. A song of David.
\q
\v 1 Hear my cry, O God,
\q2 and heed my prayer;
\q
\v 2 from earth’s far end I call to thee,
\q2 my heart is fainting.
\q When troubles are too strong for me,
\q2 do thou direct me,
\q
\v 3 O thou who art my refuge,
\q2 a fortress against the foe.
\q
\v 4 Oh to be a guest of thine for ever!
\q2 oh to be sheltered underneath thy wings!
\q
\v 5 For thou hearest my vows, O God,
\q2 thou grantest the desire of reverent men.
\q
\v 6 Add many a day to the life of the king,
\q2 till his years are age on age.
\q
\v 7 May he sit on his throne before God for all time!
\q2 Bid thy love and loyalty safeguard him.
\q
\v 8 And I will ever sing thy praise,
\q2 paying my vows through all my days.

\c 62
\d From the Choirmaster’s collection. To Jeduthun’s tune. A song of David.
\q
\v 1 Leave it all quietly to God, my soul,
\q2 my rescue comes from him alone;
\q
\v 2 rock, rescue, refuge, he is all to me,
\q2 never shall I be overthrown.
\b
\q
\v 3 How long will you be threatening a man,
\q2 you murderers all,
\q as if he were a shaky fence,
\q2 a tottering wall?
\b
\q
\v 4 They plan to push me from my place,
\q2 delighting in a crafty part;
\q blessings are on their lips,
\q2 and curses in their heart.
\b
\q
\v 5 Leave it all quietly to God, my soul,
\q2 my rescue comes from him alone;
\q
\v 6 rock, rescue, refuge, he is all to me,
\q2 never shall I be overthrown.
\b
\q
\v 7 My safety and my honur rest on God;
\q2 God is my strong rock and refuge.
\q
\v 8 Always rely on him, my followers,
\q2 pour out your prayers to him;
\q2 God is a refuge for us.
\b
\q
\v 9 The lower ranks are but a thing of naught,
\q2 the upper ranks are only a delusion;
\q weigh them, they prove to be lighter and slighter than a breath of air.
\b
\q
\v 10 Rely not on extortion,
\q2 pride not yourselves on robbery;
\q if wealth increases,
\q2 set not your heart upon it.
\b
\q
\v 11 There is one thing God has said;
\q2 aye, twice have I heard him say it:
