\q2 from brimming streams divine;
\q thou provides the grain
\q2 by preparing her duly,
\q
\v 10 watering well her furrows,
\q2 soaking her ridges,
\q softening her with showers,
\q2 and blessing all her growth.
\q
\v 11 Thou art crowning the year with thy goodness,
\q rich stores drop where thou passest,
\q
\v 12 the very pastures of the downs o’erflow,
\q2 the hills wear girdles of joy,
\q
\v 13 the meadows are clothed with flocks,
\q2 the valleys covered with corn,
\q2 shouting and singing for joy.

\c 66
\d From the Choirmaster’s collection. A song for music.
\q
\v 1 Sing homage, all the earth, to God,
\q2
\v 2 sing out the glory fo his name,
\q2 and celebrate his praises.
\q
\v 3 Say this to God: “How dread thy deeds are!
\q2 thine enemies cower
\q2 before thy power;
\q
\v 4 all the earth bows to thee,
\q2 singing thy praise,
\q2 singing praise to thy name.”
\q
\v 5 Come and see what God has done,
\q2 how dread his deeds are among men.
\q
\v 6 He turns the sea to dry land,
\q2 till men cross floods on foot.
\q So let us joy in him
\q2
\v 7 who rules for ever by his power,
\q whose eyes survey the nations,
\q2 till not a rebel dares to raise his head.
\q
\v 8 Bless our God, O nation,
\q2 sound his praise aloud,
\q
\v 9 who keeps us safe in life,
\q2 and never lets us come to grief.
\q
\v 10 For, though thou hast put us to the proof, O God,
\q2 testing our mettle, like silver,
\q
\v 11 though thou hast let us be captured,
\q2 let us be heavily chained,
\q2
\v 12 let conquerors ride over us,
\q though we had to pass through fire and water,
\q2 yet thou hast granted us a rich relief,
\q2 past set us free in liberty.
\b
\q
\v 13 So I enter thy house with sacrifices,
\q2 I will pay my vows to thee,
\q
\v 14 vows poured out by my lips,
\q2 vows uttered in my agony;
\q
\v 15 fat beasts I will offer thee,
\q2 the odour of burning rams,
\q2 bullocks and goats in sacrifice.
\b
\q
\v 16 Come, all ye worshippers of God,
\q2 hear what he did for me:
\q
\v 17 no sooner had I called to him
\q2 than I was praising him for answering me.
\q
\v 18 Had I been thinking secretly of sin,
\q2 the Lord would never have listened;
\q
\v 19 but God has listened indeed,
\q2 and to my prayer he has paid heed.
\q
\v 20 Blessed be God who has not checked
\q2 my prayer to him, nor is own love to me.

\c 67
\d From the Choirmaster’s collection. A song for a string accompaniment.
\q
\v 1 O God, bless us with thy favour,
\q2 may thy face smile on us.
\q
\v 2 that so thy purpose may be plain to men,
\q2 thy saving power to every nation.
\q
\v 3 O God, may the world praise thee,
\q2 may all races praise thee,
\q
\v 4 may the nations sing for joy,
\q2 for thou rulest the world justly,
\q2 thou guidest the nations on earth!
\q
\v 5 O God, may the world praise thee,
\q2 may all the races praise thee!
\q
\v 6 The land has yielded her harvest
\q2 by the blessing of God, our God;
\q
\v 7 bless us, O God, bless us,
\q2 till men rever thee to the world’s far end.

\c 68
\d From the Choirmaster’s collection. A song of David, for music.
\q
\v 1 When God stirs, his enemies scatter,
\q those who hate him fly before him;
\q
\v 2 as smoke is driven before the wind,
\q2 as wax melts at a fire,
\q2 so the ungodly perish before God.
\q
\v 3 But good men before God rejoice,
\q2 exulting with a joyful voice.
\b
\q
\v 4 Sing to God, celebrate his name,
\q2 extol him who rides on the clouds,
\q2 bless him, exult before him,
\q
\v 5 before God in his sacred home,
\q2 father of orphans, champion of widows,
\q
\v 6 the God who brings the lonely home,
\q2 and frees the prisoner for prosperity—
\q2 only the rebels have to live forlorn.
\b
\q
\v 7 O God, when thou didst march before thy people,
\q2 when thou didst move across the steppes,
\q
\v 8 earth was quaking, the skies shaking,
\q2 before God, Israel’s God.
\q
\v 9 O God, thou didst pour down a generous rain,
\q2 reviving thy land as it languished;
\q
\v 10 thy household were settled there,
\q2 and in thy goodness thou didst meet their needs.
\b
\q
\v 11 When the Lord sent news of victory,
\q2 the women who told it were a mighty host:
\q
\v 12 “Kings and their armies are flying, are flying,
\q2 their spoil is divided
\q2 by Israel the fair Dove at home,
\q
\v 13 till her wings are covered with silver,
\q2 her pinions shimmer in gold.
\q
\v 14 When the kins were routed on the field,
\q2 it was like snow falling on mount Zalmon.”
\b
\q
\v 15 A mighty range is Bashan range,
\q2 Bashan range has many a peak.
\q
\v 16 But what is your grudge, O range of peaks,
\q2 at the hill that God loves for his home,
\q2 where the Eternal dwells for evermore?
\q
\v 17 With mighty chariots in their myriads
\q2 the Eternal came from Sinai to this sanctuary.
\q
\v 18 There didst thou triump, with captives in thy train,
\q2 with tribute taken from men—
\q2 only the rebels dwell not there with God.
\b
\q
\v 19 Blessed be the Lord, our saving God,
\q2 who daily bears the burden of our life;
\q
\v 20 God is for us a God of victories,
\q2 thanks to the Eternal we escape from death;
\q
\v 21 yes, God will shatter the head of his foes,
\q2 each long-haired sinner who defies him.
\q
\v 22 The Lord’s word is, “Wherever you may be,
\q2 I bring you from Bashan, from the sea,
\q
\v 23 to bathe your feet in the blood of the foe
\q2 and let your dogs share, as they lap it.”
